1. Foundational Design Principles

1. Physics‑First (Extreme)
   · Conservative dynamics (gravity, inertia, orbital mechanics) are analytically expressed.
   · Neural components learn only what cannot be modeled from first principles: plume‑surface coupling, low‑Reynolds aerodynamics, and sensor degradation.
2. GNSS‑Independent Navigation
   · No reliance on global satellite constellations.
   · State estimation relies on Visual‑Inertial Odometry (VIO), LiDAR SLAM, and Celestial Navigation (Star/Sun sensors).
3. Passive & Active Thermal Stability
   · No convective cooling (fans). Thermal management relies on radiative heat transfer, conductive heat piping, and resistive heating.
   · Computational load is throttled based on radiative thermal headroom.
4. Radiation‑Hardened Logic
   · Software architecture includes Single Event Upset (SEU) detection and Triple Modular Redundancy (TMR) for critical control loops.
   · Shielding specifications defined for critical avionics.
5. Safety by Construction (Autonomous)
   · Formal guarantees: Lipschitz bounds, energy drift monitoring, and "Safe Haven" autonomous landing protocols.
   · All neural outputs are clamped and validated by a low‑level safety layer independent of ground control.
6. Modular Adaptability
   · Central avionics stack remains common; propulsion and airframe interfaces are modular to support both Lunar and Martian profiles.

