8. Thermal Model (Radiative)

Since convection is absent (Lunar) or negligible (Mars), the thermal model is purely radiative with conduction.

The junction temperature $T_j$ is modeled as:

P_{\text{diss}} = \epsilon \sigma A (T_j^4 - T_{\text{sink}}^4) + G_{\text{cond}} (T_j - T_{\text{struct}}) + P_{\text{heater}} 

Where:

· $P_{\text{diss}}$: Power dissipated by compute.
· $\epsilon$: Emissivity of radiator surface (e.g., 0.9 for white paint).
· $\sigma$: Stefan‑Boltzmann constant ($5.67 \times 10^{-8}\,\text{W/m}^2\text{K}^4$).
· $A$: Radiator surface area ($0.1\,\text{m}^2$).
· $T_{\text{sink}}$: Effective space sink temperature (≈ 3 K) or Martian ambient (can drop to 150 K at night).
· $G_{\text{cond}}$: Conductance to spacecraft structure (e.g., 0.5 W/K).
· $P_{\text{heater}}$: Resistive heating power (Kapton film) – activated when $T_j$ drops below –20 °C.

Control Logic:

· If $T_j$ approaches 80 °C, reduce inference frequency $f_{\text{inf}}$ and gate capsules ($z_i \to 0$) to lower $P_{\text{diss}}$.
· If $T_j$ < –20 °C, activate heaters to maintain minimum operating temperature.

