9. Navigation Mathematics (GNSS‑Denied)

9.1 Visual‑Inertial Odometry (VIO) EKF

State vector: $\hat{x} = [p, v, q, b_a, b_g]^\top$, where $q$ is quaternion, $b_a, b_g$ are accelerometer and gyro biases.

Process Model: IMU measurements $\tilde{a}, \tilde{\omega}$ are used to propagate:
\dot{p} = v,\quad \dot{v} = R(q)(\tilde{a} - b_a) + g,\quad \dot{q} = \frac{1}{2} \Omega(\tilde{\omega} - b_g) q,\quad \dot{b}_a = 0,\quad \dot{b}_g = 0 


with additive noise.

Measurement Updates:

· Visual Features: Reprojection error of tracked features (stereo camera) – provides relative pose update.
· LiDAR: Point‑to‑plane constraints (when available) – provides altitude and local shape.
· Star Tracker: Absolute attitude correction (quaternion update) – used when vehicle is stable.

The EKF runs at 500 Hz, with corrections applied at the arrival rate of each sensor.

9.2 Terrain Relative Navigation (TRN)

To correct long‑term drift, onboard LiDAR or camera data is matched against orbital maps (e.g., LRO or MRO data).

· Algorithm: Iterative Closest Point (ICP) or Feature Matching between observed point cloud and stored Digital Elevation Model (DEM).
· Integration: TRN position fix is treated as a pseudo‑measurement in the EKF with low frequency (1 Hz) but high confidence.
· Math: Minimize $\sum \| p_{\text{obs}} - T_{\text{map}}(p_{\text{ref}}) \|^2$ where $T_{\text{map}}$ transforms map coordinates to the observed frame.

