Appendix H: Thermal and Power Management

H.1 Radiator Sizing

From the radiative heat equation, we solve for required area $A$ given maximum allowable $T_j$ and worst‑case $P_{\text{diss}}$. For Lunar day, $T_{\text{sink}}$ may be as high as 120 °C (393 K) due to solar radiation on the radiator if not properly oriented. To mitigate, radiators are placed on sides that can be oriented away from the sun, or a variable emissivity surface is used. Worst‑case $T_{\text{sink}}$ is assumed to be 300 K (moderate). With $P_{\text{diss}}=15\,\text{W}$, $T_j=353\,\text{K}$, $\epsilon=0.9$, we get:

A = \frac{15}{0.9 \times 5.67\times10^{-8} \times (353^4 - 300^4)} \approx 0.12\,\text{m}^2 

Thus $A=0.15\,\text{m}^2$ provides margin.

H.2 Heater Control

Resistive heaters are attached to critical components (battery, IMU, compute). They are controlled by thermostats with hysteresis: turn on at $T < -20°C$, turn off at $T > -10°C$. Power for heaters is drawn from the battery; the energy budget must account for night survival.

